definition.value: The stable isotope of xenon with relative atomic mass 128.904780, 26.4 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 1/2.
The stable isotope of gold with relative atomic mass 196.966552, 100 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 3/2.
The stable isotope of vanadium with relative atomic mass 50.943964, 99.8 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 7/2.
A stable isotope of selenium with relative atomic mass 76.919915, 7.60 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 1/2.
The stable isotope of lithium with relative atomic mass 7.016004, 92.5 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 3/2.
The stable isotope of rubidium with relative atomic mass 86.909184, 27.9 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 3/2.
The stable isotope of niobium with relative atomic mass 92.906378, 100 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 9/2.
The stable isotope of niobium with relative atomic mass 182.950225, 14.3 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 1/2.
A compound of the general formula M-ER where E is a chalcogen and R is an organyl group.
A compound of the general formula M-SeR where R is an organyl group.
A uranium coordination entity consisting of uranium(V) bound to two pentamethylcyclopentadienyl groups, a 2,6-diisopropylanilino group (via a U=N bond) and a phenyltelluryl group.
A compound of the general formula M-TeR where R is an organyl group
The first intermediate in the biosynthesis of vitamin B12 from uroporphyrinogen III, in which one methyl group has been introduced at position 2 of the tetrapyrrole framework.
A compound of the general formula M-SR where R is an organyl group.
A linear amino trisaccharide consisting of alpha-neuraminyl, beta-D-galactosyl and N-acetyl-D-glucosamine residues linked in a (2->3) and (1->4) sequence.
An organosulfonic ester of the general formula CF3SO3R where R is an organyl group.
A compound of the general formula HSO2OR where R is an organyl group.
A compound of general formula CH3C(=O)SR where R is an organyl group.
A compound with the general formula R'-N=C(OR)R'' where R is organyl and R' and R'' can be organyl or H.
A compound of the general formula R'-N=C(OR)SO2R''.
A cobalt corrinoid that is precorrin-7 in which the four pyrrole-type nitrogens are bound to a central cobalt atom.
A metalloporphyrin that is sirohydrochlorin in which the four nitrogen atoms are bound to a central cobalt atom.
A mixture composed from maneb and zineb, which is used as a broad-spectrum contact fungicide.
An organic heterocyclyl group consisting of a purine with a free valence at one of the ring atoms.
An organic heterocyclyl group consisting of a pyrimidine with a free valence at one of the ring atoms.

A polymeric complex of manganese with the ethylene bis(dithiocarbamate) anionic ligand. An agrochemical fungicide, it is used to control a variety of diseases including blight, leaf spot, rust, downy mildew and scab.

A polymeric complex of zinc with the ethylene bis(dithiocarbamate) anionic ligand. Formerly used as an agricultural fungicide for the control of downy mildews and rusts, its use is no longer permitted in the US or the EU.

A cobalt-corrinoid heptacarboxylic acid with 8 methyl groups at positions 1, 2, 5, 7, 12, 15, 17; -CH2COOH groups at positions 2, 7, 18; -CH2CH2COOH groups at positions 3, 8, 13, 17; and divalent cobalt centred among the four nitrogens. It is a part of the vitamin B12 structure.
A pyranone substituted with one or more halogen atoms.
A pyranone substituted with one or more bromine atoms.
